{
  "text": "Population synthesis is based on an iterative fitting approach [CITATION_1] using the variables household size and number of cars at the household level and age group, sex, and employment status on the level of persons. Actual households are generated using weighted random draws from a household travel survey. Workplaces and education places are assigned based on existing commuting matrices taking the travel distance reported in the household survey into account. The number of cars is a result of population synthesis, the actual type of the cars is modelled by a car ownership model [CITATION_2] Transit pass ownership is determined based on a binary logit model.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "154218811",
    "[CITATION_2]": "30381042"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "154218811": {
      "title": "Creating synthetic baseline populations",
      "abstract": "To develop activity-based travel models using microsimulation, individual travelers and households must be considered. Methods for creating baseline synthetic populations of households and persons using 1990 census data are given. Summary tables from the Census Bureau STF-3A are used in conjunction with the Public Use Microdata Sample (PUMS), and Iterative Proportional Fitting (IPF) is applied to estimate the proportion of households in a block group or census tract with a desired combination of demographics. Households are generated by selection of households from the associated PUMS according to these proportions. The tables of demographic proportions which are exploited here to make household selections from the PUMS may be used in traditional modeling. The procedures are validated by creating pseudo census tracts from PUMS samples and considering the joint distribution of the size of households and the number of vehicles in the households. It is shown that the joint distributions created by these methods do not differ substantially from the true values. Additionally the effects of small changes in the procedure, such as imputation of additional demographics and adding partial counts to the constructed demographic tables are discussed in the paper."
    },
    "30381042": {
      "title": "Assessing the effects of a growing electric vehicle fleet using a microscopic travel demand model",
      "abstract": "The German government targets to increase the number of electric vehicles (EV) in the German car fleet to 1 million in 2020. Since the characteristics of EVs differ partly from conventional cars (e.g. in driving range, local emissions, electric energy demand), there is a growing need for an assessment of EV ownership and EV usage. A number of studies are available that forecast the future EV market shares. However, the results of these studies are not directly transferable into future everyday travel behaviour especially when considering the characteristics of EVs. In transport research, the development and application of microscopic travel demand models is a common approach to simulate the impact of new technologies. Since these types of models are capable of simulating individual behaviour, the analysis of processes like charging is possible on a disaggregated level. A multi-day simulation provides more detailed information due to the modelled temporal variation of travel behaviour. Hence, we used the microscopic travel demand model mobiTopp to simulate the effects of different market penetration scenarios of EVs over a simulation period of a whole week. MobiTopp was used to simulate the travel behaviour and car usage exemplarily in the greater Stuttgart area for the year 2025. The model contains 2.5 million inhabitants who own 1.3 million cars. Within this fleet, we distinguish conventional combustion vehicles (CV) and two different types of EVs: battery electric vehicles (BEVs) and extended range electric vehicles (EREVs). For the integration of EVs in mobiTopp, two extensions were necessary: an \u201cEV ownership model\u201d and an \u201cEV usage model\u201d. One challenge was to ensure that EVs are allocated to those households and persons, which are likely to own an EV in 2025. Therefore, we developed an \u201cEV ownership model\u201d in order to assign EVs to households and to car users. It is a combination of a logit model, which assesses the suitability of an EV for a person, and similarity measure model, which assesses the acceptance of EVs. Two datasets were used to construct the models: data from a car usage model integrating long distance events (CUMILE) and data on EV user characteristics from the MINI E Berlin field trial. The logit model has been estimated based on the CUMILE model data, showing the daily mileages over a period of a full year for a representative German car fleet. These results were used in order to analyse which person groups are suited and therefore more likely to replace their existing car by an EV from the car usage perspective. The MINI E Berlin field trial was a large scale EV field study with a sample of potential early adopters of EVs. The EV acceptance model is based on a similarity measure that identifies mobiTopp\u2019s agents that are similar to the participants of the MINI E Berlin field trial based on socio-demographic characteristics. The \u201cEV usage model\u201d simulates of the battery level of the EVs (i.e., discharging during usage, charging when stopped at a location with charging facilities). It also takes the limited range of BEVs into account, since BEV users can only use their BEVs to go to destinations within the battery range. The availability of charging facilities is scenario-dependent, different scenarios with charging facilities at home and charging facilities at work have been simulated. In the mobiTopp model, a car always starts charging, when parked at a location with charging facilities. It stops charging either when the battery is full or when the car is used again. The limited range of BEVs is considered in the destination choice and in the mode choice model. The destination choice model has been altered, so that for discretionary activities (e.g. shopping, leisure) the BEV user can only choose destinations within the BEV range. The mode choice model has been modified, as the mode car is not allowed for destinations beyond the BEV range, if the only available car is a BEV. The mobiTopp simulation results show that EVs are used less intensively than conventional cars: the weekly mileage of conventional cars is 270 km on average, while EREVs cover 240 km and BEVs cover 90 km. Reasons for the lower weekly mileages of BEVs are shorter trips made with BEVs on average as well as a lower trip frequency using BEVs. The weekly mileage of EREVs in battery electric mode is 160 km on average. This indicates that both BEVs and EREVs have the potential to reduce local emissions. The energy demand caused by EV usage without a controlled charging strategy peaks every day between 6 p.m. and 7 p.m. This results in an imposing temporal burden on the electric grid."
    }
  }
}